    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-05T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-05T19:00:00-05:00" n="673"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">102.1/10537b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-05T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 5, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>437. For Adler from the Secretary of the Treasury. Meeting was held in Treasury
                    on March 30 together with representatives of War and State Departments to
                    discuss proposal outlined in paragraph 2 of your cable of March 28.<note n="88"
                        xml:id="d673fn88">Telegram No. 541, <ref target="#pg_909">p.
                        909</ref>.</note> Approval was given by War, State and Treasury to this
                    proposal and we presume that General Stilwell has already been so informed by
                    War Department.</p>
                <p>With regard to sale of gold on joint account to raise part of our <hi
                        rend="italic">fapi</hi> requirements, Treasury has informed War and State
                    that, as indicated on past occasions, we are in favor of such program. The
                    Treasury presumes from information received that Ambassador Gauss and General
                    Stilwell are also in favor of such program.</p>
                <p>Therefore, as soon as agreement has been reached with regard to the financing of
                    U. S. Army program in China, propose to Dr. Kung sale of gold and/or U. S.
                    dollar currency on joint account to meet all United States governmental
                    expenditures, except those of the Army.</p>
                <p>Reference your cables of March 28, 1944, No. 541 and March 23, No. 517, and our
                    cable of March 8, 1944, No. 314.<note n="89" xml:id="d673fn89">Telegram No. 314
                        not printed: for substance, see footnote 84, <ref target="#pg_907">p.
                            907</ref>.</note> [Morgenthau.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
